      "text": "Contents\n\n/ /\n\n## 2024 STATE OF THE MARKET REPORT FOR THE ERCOT ELECTRICITY MARKETS\n\n### Independent Market Monitor for ERCOT\n\n### July 2025\n\nRevision Summary\n\n/ /\n\n## REVISIONS TO THE MAY 2024 REPORT\n\nWe received feedback from ERCOT on the State of the Market Report we published in May. \nThis page will briefly describe the revisions we applied to this version of the report. \nScaling Factor on Figure \nIn Chapter I.G.2. Assessment of ECRS Procurement Quantities, the scaling factor we applied to \nthe vertical axis in Figure 10 was incorrect. The updated figure took its place. \nCollateral Requirements \nIn Chapter III.B.3. Collateral Requirements, we conflated total collateral requirements with total \ncollateral held by ERCOT in one paragraph. We also concluded incorrectly that collateral \nrequirements were disincentivizing some generators from participating in the day-ahead market. \nWe reviewed our revisions with the ERCOT Credit team, and they can also be found in Chapter \nIII.B.3. \nIncorrect Units \nIn Chapter VI.C.1. Interpreting Single-Year Net Revenues, we corrected using units of $/MWh \nto describe the cost of new entry and replaced them with the correct units of $/kW-yr. \nDemand Response in CDR Report \nIn our commentary on Chapter VI.G.2. Capacity, Demand, and Reserves Report, we noted that \nthe report does not incorporate demand response into its demand forecast. The CDR report does \ntake into account the Emergency Response Service (ERS). We updated the language in that \nsection to reflect that. \nOfficer Letter Loads in May 2024 CDR \nIn Chapter VI.H.1 Load Forecast Chronology, we incorrectly noted that the May 2024 CDR \nreport did not include officer letter loads. The report includes them but did not treat them at \nlength since NPRR 1180 and PGRR 107 had not yet been approved and finalized at the date of \npublication. \nERCOT Market at a Glance Tables \nIn Appendix I: Statistics at a Glance, we included the wrong number for the “Energy” line item \nin Table A1. This error carried through to the “Energy” line item in Table A2. We corrected the \nnumbers in both tables’ line items. \n\nContents\n\n/ /\n\nTABLE OF CONTENTS\n\nCharacteristics of Supply and Demand ... ii \nReview of Market Performance ... iii \nCompetition and Market Power ... viii \nEvolution of Supply and Demand in ERCOT ... ix \nFuture Market Design Improvements ... xiii \nRecommendations ... xvi \nA. Real-Time Market Prices ... 1 \nB. Zonal Energy Prices ... 5 \nC. Shortage and Reliability Pricing ... 5 \nD. Aggregated Offer Curves ... 7 \nE. Real-Time Prices Adjusted for Fuel Price Changes ... 9 \nF. Exposure of Load to Real-Time Prices ... 10 \nG. Impact of ECRS on Real-Time Market Prices ... 10 \nA. ERCOT Load in 2024 ... 15 \nB. Generation Capacity in ERCOT ... 16 \nC. Wind and Solar Output in ERCOT ... 17 \nD. Imports to ERCOT ... 20 \nE. Energy Storage Resources ... 20 \nF. Demand Response Capability ... 26 \nA. Day-Ahead Energy Market Pricing ... 37 \nB. Day-Ahead Market Activity ... 38 \nC. Point-to-Point Obligations ... 42 \nD. Ancillary Services Market ... 44 \nA. Day-Ahead Congestion ... 48 \nB. Real-Time Congestion ... 49 \nC. CRR Market Outcomes and Revenue Sufficiency ... 53 \nD. Real-Time Congestion Shortfalls ... 58 \nE. Load Zone Configuration ... 59 \nA. Reliability Unit Commitments ... 65 \nB. Thermal Generation Outages and Deratings ... 69 \nC. QSE Operation Planning ... 71 \nD. Firm Fuel Supply Service ... 72 \nA. Introduction ... 75 \nB. Net Revenue Analysis ... 78 \nC. Cost of New Entry and Net Revenues ... 79 \n\nContents\n\n/ /\n\nD. Profitability of Additional Resource Classes ... 81 \nE. Peaker Net Margin ... 82 \nF. ERCOT’s Reliability Standard ... 84 \nG. Communicating Resource Adequacy ... 86 \nH. Load Forecast ... 91 \nI. Generation Forecast ... 98 \nJ. Conclusion ... 98 \nA. Structural Market Power Indicators ... 101 \nB. Evaluation of Supplier Conduct ... 103 \nC. Voluntary Mitigation Plans ... 106 \nD. Market Power Mitigation ... 108 \nA. Ancillary Services Provided in Real-Time ... A-5 \nB. Supplemental Ancillary Services Market ... A-8 \n\nContents\n\n/ /\n\nLIST OF FIGURES \nFigure 1: Average All-in Cost for Electricity in ERCOT, 2020-2024 ... 2 \nFigure 2: Prices by Time of Day, May-September 2020-2024 ... 3 \nFigure 3: Impact of Price Spikes on Real-Time Energy Price, 2023-2024 ... 4 \nFigure 4: Impact of the ORDC on Real-Time Prices ... 6 \nFigure 5: Impact of the RDPA on Real-Time Prices ... 7 \nFigure 6: Aggregated Generation Offer Stack – Annual, Peak and Net Peak Load ... 8 \nFigure 7: Monthly and Annual Implied Heat Rates, 2020-2024 ... 9 \nFigure 8: Monthly Average Load Exposure, 2020-2024 ... 10 \nFigure 9: Increase in Ancillary Services Procurement ... 11 \nFigure 10: Annual LOLP vs. Decrease in ECRS Procurement Volume ... 12 \nFigure 11: Excess Cost of ECRS Deployment Practice, 2024 ... 14 \nFigure 12: Annual Load Statistics by Zone, 2020-2024 ... 15 \nFigure 13: Installed Generation Capacity in ERCOT, 2015-2024 ... 16 \nFigure 14: Installed Capacity by Resource Type for Each Zone, 2024 ... 17 \nFigure 15: Wind Production and Curtailment, 2018-2024 ... 18 \nFigure 16: Solar Production and Curtailment, 2018-2024 ... 18 \nFigure 17: Top and Bottom Deciles (Hours) of Net Load, 2020-2024 ... 19 \nFigure 18: Annual Energy Transacted Across DC Ties ... 20 \nFigure 19: ESR Installed Capacity, 2020-2024 ... 22 \nFigure 20: ESR Participation in Ancillary Services, 2022-2024 ... 23 \nFigure 21: Net Injection of Power from ESRs in 2024 ... 24 \nFigure 22: Average Aggregate Offers for ESRs to Buy or Sell Energy, 2020-2024 ... 25 \nFigure 23: Total and Normalized ESR Revenue, 2020-2024 ... 26 \nFigure 24: Non-Coincident and Simultaneous Peak Demand for LFLs ... 27 \nFigure 25: Responsive Reserves from UFR and FFR in DAM ... 29 \nFigure 26: Average Aggregate Load for CLRs, 2022-2024 ... 30 \nFigure 27: Average Aggregate Bid Curves